## Git

- Always keep commit subject 72 characters or less. Prefer 50 or less. Don't truncate blindly.
  Prefer semantic meaning over implementation details.
- Include enough context in the commit subject for someone scanning `git log`
  to understand the scope. Qualify ambiguous nouns with their parent system
  (e.g., "Fix Claude statusline spacing" not "Fix statusline spacing").
- Prefer atomic commits: if changes span multiple unrelated areas, split them
  into separate commits — one logical change per commit.
- Wrap commit body at 72 characters, when possible
- Always run project-specific build before committing
- Always use `--force-with-lease` to force push, when necessary
- Always set `AI_AGENT=1` when running git commands that trigger GPG signing (e.g., commit, tag)
- When squash-merging a PR, always provide your own summarized commit message
  that includes the PR reference suffix (e.g., ` (#1234)`).
  Do not accept the default squash message (concatenated individual commits).
- When creating a PR, always ask whether to open it as a draft or ready for review.
- Never push to a remote unless explicitly told to.
- Never force push to main/master.
- Only force push when rewriting commits that were already pushed to the
  remote. A local-only amend does NOT require a force push — just push
  normally. Check `git status` against the tracking branch before deciding.
- When creating issues or PRs, always use the repository's issue/PR templates if available.
- Always delete the local and remote PR branch atomically when merging
  (e.g., `gh pr merge --delete-branch`).
  Do not merge first and then delete the branch as a separate step.
- If `gh pr merge --delete-branch` succeeds but prints a git error like
  `fatal: 'main' is already used by worktree at ...`, the PR merged and
  the remote branch was deleted — only the local branch deletion failed
  because the base branch is checked out in another worktree. This is
  expected in linked worktrees. Do NOT re-run the merge command. The
  local branch will be cleaned up when the worktree is removed.
- Claude Code replaces `/` with `+` in worktree directory and branch names
  (e.g., `-w fix/foo` creates branch `worktree-fix+foo`). When resolving the
  original branch name, replace `+` back to `/` after stripping the `worktree-`
  prefix.
- When checking out a `worktree-` branch, check if a remote tracking branch
  exists without the prefix (e.g., `origin/fix/foo` for `worktree-fix+foo`).
  If so, set it as upstream:
  `git branch --set-upstream-to=origin/fix/foo worktree-fix+foo`.
- When pushing a branch that starts with `worktree-`, strip the prefix and
  restore `/` from `+` in the remote refspec
  (e.g., `git push -u origin worktree-fix+foo:fix/foo`). This keeps remote
  branch names clean while preserving the local worktree convention.
- When running in a linked worktree, always search, read, and edit files
  within the worktree directory. Never fall back to the base working tree
  for file operations — the worktree has its own copy of the repo.
- When merging the current branch into another and you know you're in a
  linked worktree (e.g., spawned via `isolation: "worktree"`), run
  `git worktree list` to find the target branch. If it's in the main
  working tree, merge from there without prompting. If it's in another
  linked worktree, prompt before merging.
